subSection.paragraph:
Flowers provide visual, olfactory, structural, and/or tactile cues informing to potential pollinators about the location of floral rewards (
Faegri and van der Pijl, 1979
), of which flower color is one of the most important in their biocommunication. The color of a flower is a consequence of the wavelength of the light it reflects, which primarily depends on the wavelengths of light absorbed by pigments and the way in which the floral structure scatters light (
van der Kooi et al., 2019
). Flowers can also fluoresce, highlighting their appearance. Biofluorescence has been observed in floral nectar (
Thorp et al., 1975
), petals (
Gandía-Herrero et al., 2005
), and anthers/pollen (
Mori et al., 2018
), and has been proposed as a visual cue for pollinating insects. The anthers and pollen of many plant species exhibit blue fluorescence under UV irradiation; a preference of honeybees (

Apis mellifera

) for blue fluorescence was found in a behavioral assay (
Mori et al., 2018
). The diversity of flower colors may reflect their adaptation to pollinators (
Fenster et al., 2004
; 
Gegear and Burns, 2007
), and alterations in flower color can drive plant speciation (
van der Niet et al., 2014
).

Bees have a visible spectrum ranging from 
300 nm
to 
650 nm
based on trichromatic vision with maximal sensitivities in the UV (
λ
Max
344 nm
), blue (
λ
Max
436 nm
), and green (
λ
Max
544 nm
) regions (
Menzel and Blakers, 1976
), and are less able to detect red as they lack a red sensitive photoreceptor (
Peitsch et al., 1992
). Bees have an innate preference for flowers reflecting light in the 
410–420 nm
range (
Giurfa et al., 1996
). In contrast, diurnal birds have four classes of photopigments in their cone cells: UV sensitive (UVS) or violet sensitive (VS); short wavelength sensitive (SWS); middle wavelength sensitive (MWS); and long wavelength sensitive (LWS), and are therefore able to detect a broader range of wavelengths of light than bees (
300–700 nm
; 
Odeen and Hastad, 2010
). Major avian pollinator hummingbirds show no innate preference for colors (
Lunau et al., 2011
). Although bees sometimes visit red flowers and birds sometimes visit non-red flowers actually, the red color of flowers has been attributed to bird pollination syndrome (
Fenster et al., 2004
). Pollination by bees can be disadvantageous due to its lower efficiency of pollen transfer than that of birds, for some plants (
Thomson and Wilson, 2008
; 
Krauss et al., 2017
). Therefore, red colors of ornithophilous plants are considered to have been evolved to avoid less effective pollinator bees, rather than bird attraction, which is the framework of the ‘bee avoidance hypothesis’ (
Raven, 1972
; 
Cronk and Ojeda, 2008
; 
Lunau et al., 2011
).

